                                Report abuseTranscript of John Clellon Holmes John Clellon Holmes John Clellon Holmes was an essayist, poet, and novelist and part of the beat generation John Clellon HolmesHe was born in Holyoke, Massachusetts, March 12, 1926.He was the son of John McClellan Holmes, a salesman, and Elizabeth Franklin Emmons HolmesDate of birth John grew up in several locations  in northeastern parts of the United States and California. Holmes was interested in writing at an early age. At the age of eleven he wrote his first poem. Childhood Holmes Dropped out of  Dwight Morrow High School in Englewood. Afterward he moved with his mother to NY where he anticipated of being drafted. Holmes took some extension courses in Columbia university in 1943, then he was drafted into the U.S. Navy Hospital Corps in June 1944Education Marriage While he was in the navy, he married Marian Miliambro, at no time did they ever have children During the war  He spent the balance of the war working in a hospital in Long Island, New York, which gave him the opportunity to read widely during slow periods; his wartime experience also transformed him into a lifelong pacifistAfter the warAfter his discharge in 1945 holmes worked odd jobs to support himself when he met Jay Landesman, the editor of Neurotica magazine, in 1948. "Tea For Two"Holmes's first published work, a short story titled "Tea for Two," was published in the periodical later in 1948. 4Th Of July During July 4th weekend of that year he met and became friends with Jack Kerouac and Allen Ginsberg. Some of the Work of HolmesSome of the books that Holmes wrote include  The Horn, Nothing More to Declare, and Go: A NovelDeath John Clellon Holmes Died Died: March 30, 1988, Middletown, CTFull transcriptMore presentations by
    
        
